Rating: 1
Rather ordinary and when I think of the amount of energy it took to run the oven that long in the summertime, I regret the expense of making this cake, that is more like a tart with a soft crust.

Rating: 4
I love this cake; I make it regularly every summer (one's in the kitchen right now) since it first appeared on the cover of Gourmet. It's so easy, beautiful, and always a hit. I add the zest of 1/2 lemon to the pastry with the wet ingredients. I use unrefined sugar (such as Sugar in the Raw or Demerara) in both filling and pastry since I find it enhances the flavor. I usually use 5 yellow peaches or nectarines and 2 cups blueberries. For the pastry I grind the sugar in the food processor before adding the rest of the dry ingredients. I instantly recognized the pastry is the same as for traditional Dutch Appeltaart (apple tart), minus the lattice top. For example, the recipe at http://dutchfood.about.com/od/breadspastriescookies/r/ApplePie.htm is similar my Dutch mother-in-law's.

Rating: 4
My husband said this is the finest! The long cook time really dries the fruits to produce a concentrated flavor and the crust is delicious. Calling it a cake is a definite misnomer, its more of a tart or Italian crostata.

Rating: 1
Totally unimpressed--basically just a peach cobbler--but not that good.

Rating: 4
Sometimes you stumble upon a recipe that makes you say, Wow! This is one of those recipes. It really does a great job highlighting the fruit. And the presentation is sure to please anyone. I would make this again in a heart beat. I followed the recipe pretty closely with only few minor changes. My fresh peaches and blueberries were wonderfully sweet so I decrease the sugar to just shy of a 1/3 c. Also I added couple additional peaches because upon examination of my crust (which only went half way up my springform pan) I felt I was a little light on the amount of fruit. Also I didn't have tapioca so I used 1 heaping T. cornstarch. I also was really worried about what color my springform pan was based on previous reviews. Was it dark grey or light grey, I really couldn't tell? So I opted for the more conservative baking temperature. I baked it at 325 for 1.5 hours, then increased the temperature to 350 for an additional 30 minutes. I can't wait to try this recipe with different combination of fruit!

Rating: 4
I've been making this recipe exactly as it is written since it came out. It's absolutely delicious. You do have to be careful about the pan you use. A clear dish works best, but even if it is a little brown, it doesn't take away from the sweetness of the fruit or the nice cakey crust.

Rating: 4
This fruit tart receives rave reviews each time I make it. I have made it with fresh and/or frozen peaches and blueberries and it turns out well each time. It is important to keep an eye on the crust, because it can brown quickly at 375. I start baking at 375, turn it down at 1 hour to 350, and finish it at that temperature. I do grind the tapioca, but I think you could do it without grinding, but might need a little more (maybe 1/2 tsp).

