Rating: 3
I had reservations about making this after reading all the reviews and comments about the cooking time, etc. I usually just go with a recipe the way it is, and not tinker with it at all. However, since I had a glass bottom, dark springform pan, I baked the cake at 325 for 80 minutes total. I used cornstarch instead of tapioca, increased the peaches to 5, and decreased the sugar a bit. I also increased the egg in the crust to about 11/2 eggs, since ours here are not really "large". What I ended up with was a cake that looks exactly like the photo, with a beautiful golden brown crust, that was not anywhere near tough or crispy. The fruit was perfectly cooked, and juicy. I made this for family, and they raved about it! This will be a recipe that I add to my dessert collection. Wonderful!

Rating: 4
I read all the reviews before making this cake and did bake the cake at 325 degrees for the first hour, because I was using a dark, 8-inch springform pan. I then increased the oven temp to 350 degrees and let it bake for another 35 minutes and it turned out great. I substituted 1 tablespoon of cornstarch for the tapioca and used almond extract instead of vanilla in the pastry, which gave it subtle flavor. I also mixed a little bit of whole wheat flour with the all-purpose flour. I decreased the sugar in the filling by two tablespoons. The key is to really let it set and cool down in the pan for 30 minutes before removing the springform. My husband loves it and wants to know when I'm making it again.

